source.guidance:
The first line needs to be the array declaration. You cannot iterate over an array that does not exist. There are three possible choices for the loop. C++ uses the `;` to separate the three parts of a for loop, so the answer with a `,` is incorrect. When using for loops, declare the iterator variable first, then create the test condition, and finally increment the iterator variable. Don't forget to indent the `cout` statement and add the `}` to terminate the loop.

```c++
string animals[4] = {"cat", "dog", "fish", "rabbit"};
for (int i = 0; i < 4; ++i) {
  cout << animals[i] << endl;
}
```

